segments.text: first, I believe, and I'm at 1001 Village Drive in College Station, getting ready to chat with Professor Emeritus Will Worley, but we're going to chat about his student experiences.
Will, now would you cast your microphone?
That's me.
All right.
Well, to help
a future user of this material, would you give a brief summary of your background and experiences before you arrived at Texas A&M to begin your studies here as a student?
Where did you grow up and what did your family do?
I'm a native of Dallas, born in October 18, 1921.
I went to grade school at James W. Fanning High School at Woodrow Wilson High School.
A unique thing about it was that it had the largest high school ROTC unit in the country.
I was a company commander there in the high school ROTC, and almost from birth I planned to come to Texas A&M, which I did starting in September 1939.
Had you ever visited the campus before you came down here to enroll?
Only once.
It was that summer, just before I enrolled.
At that time, they were just finishing the 12 dormitories, and so I lived in dormitory one, a core dorm.
In fact, all the dormitories on the campus were core dorms then.
They also had some project houses, which were on the campus.
Each county had
had a project house that they sponsored.
Let's go back.
When you came down to enroll, how did you get down here and what did you bring in terms of gear and paraphernalia?
I came with a mother and a classmate who I went to school with at Woodrow and each of us came with one footlocker and that was it.
She let us out and drove back home and we were on our own.
He got into the chemical warfare, and I got into the Signal Corps unit.
What was in your footlocker?

Well, my mother bought a new blanket, and we had sheets, and we had very little civilian clothes because as soon as we got here, then they would issue GI clothes, a blouse, a shirt or two, a pair of pants, and then we had to buy other things.
clothing that we need, but we wore uniforms all the time.
We had to have our own jackets.
We did, I think, have a sort of a raincoat, an all-weather raincoat, and this is all we had.
We also had to get an IES study lamp.
This was required, a good study lamp.
Did she let you out near your dorm?
At our dorm, within a little ways, and then she went on home.
What was your first contact with Aggie ways, with orders, directives, or anything else?
Well, of course, as freshmen, while we were the lowest form of life, and the sophomores oriented us in a hurry,
They really were the ones that kept us in line, and then the juniors and the seniors.
But the seniors monitored the juniors, and the juniors monitored the sophomores, and the sophomores took care of us.
Now this is September 1939.
Yes.
You and your outfit?
B Signal Corps.
We had three Signal Corps outfits.

practically all of us were majoring in electrical engineering, which was fortunate in a way because then you ate together, you slept together, you went to class together, you waited on upperclassmen all together.
And so it was a very enduring relationship that has persisted even now.
Describe a typical day of classes, not a weekend day, but a weekday,
describe a typical day.
When did it begin and what happened and when did it end that fall?
All right.
First we got up and went outside and had a yell practice.
Then we came back in and we cleaned up our room and then we cleaned up an upperclassman's room.
And this was until about seven o'clock when we woke up our upperclassman.
It so happens I was the room orderly for the company commander and his

Then we fell out for a mess, and we marched the mess from dormitory one up to the other end of the dining hall, and we sat next to an upperclassman, and we gave him meal service, which meant we waited on him while he sat at the table with him and be sure that he had everything wanted that was on the table.
And usually they ate, and then they left, and we ate at the same time, but they started eating before we got to eat.
All right, and then classes?
All right, then, of course, we went back to the dormitory and finished up cleaning our own room.
Usually classes started at 8 o'clock, so then we went to class till noon.
We came back to the dorm, and then we marched a mess again.
and then classes in the afternoon, and then we marched to Mass.
In the fall semester during the football season, we had Yale practice four times a week, Monday after supper, Tuesday, and then Thursday, and then Friday night.
And we had Yale practice in front of the YMCA.
The band was up at the top of the steps,
and the Yelp leaders in front of them, and the freshmen on the sidewalk, the sophomores and the juniors in the street, and the seniors behind the underclassmen.
So this lasted about 30 minutes.
And then the freshmen needed to run back to the dormitory and get there before the sophomores got back.
And we had a little Yelp practice there.
And then at 7.30, we went into our room and studied until 10 o'clock.
And then we're supposed to go on to bed by 11 o'clock, so that was the day.
If you had any time during the day not scheduled for classes or any other activities, where did you spend that time?
We were supposed to come back to our dormitory and be available for errands for the upperclassmen.
Did you do that or did you go off to the library or somewhere?
Well, we mostly came back.
We couldn't go in the YMCA.
That was for upperclassmen.
They had a bowling alley and they played ping pong.
We could go there on Sunday morning.
That's when they had church services.
Let's see.
Describe some of the incidents that today would be identified as hazing that you remember from your freshman and or sophomore years.
Well, of course, hazing, you did run errands.
That wasn't the type of hazing, I guess.
But we had bleed meetings.
This is where we got out in the hall with the sophomores, and the sophomores would bleed at us.
You know, they would gripe at us how sorry we were and that sort of thing.
And then we would have an ass tear, maybe.
Which, of course, using paddles on our behind.
That was the main thing.
Did you ever get paddled for something you didn't do?
Well, yeah, we did this.
This is part of it, I guess.
I don't know.
But, you know, after a few weeks, we all had to study.
And so this sort of thing kind of died, you might say, and it settled down to normal routine.
After those first few weeks, I was sure glad I was here because of the comrades we developed, these lifelong relationships that we still
have contact with and this sort of thing, and they didn't have time for us anyway.
They had their own studies to take care of.
Now, you were in the new dorm area?
I was in the new dormitory.
These were brand new dorms.
There was 12 of them.
Let's see.
Did you all refer to fish old ladies in those days?
Oh, yeah.
Our roommate was an old lady.
And did that friendship for you, was that a lasting one, your old lady?
Is that what?
A lasting friendship?
Oh, it is.
We went out to see him in Arizona just this last fall.
He now has had a stroke.
And, of course, he can't drive around, but he can talk fine and visit pretty well.
Let's see.
You had selected your major before you got here.
No, it was a coincidence, but it so happened.
He went to Woodrow Wilson, too.
He finished in January and went to school another semester.
And so we just showed up together.
We were roommates.
I'm not sure how it happened, but
Fortunately, he did.
When did you select your major, electrical engineering?
Right away.
Oh, yeah.
And one of the reasons I did it was because my father was with Graybar Electric Company.
He was in the electrical business, and it was at his suggestion, and I just went ahead and signed up for electrical engineering, and this is what I finished in.
Now, was electrical engineering at that time thought of
as a new discipline kind of out front on the edge of new knowledge?
Well, it was a state of the art.
At that time, it was more power than electronics.
We also had transmission, but the main job opportunities for us was to go with utilities
go with the telephone company or go with GE or Westinghouse or Alice Chalmers.
They were all in the areas of power in the telephone company, of course.
And that's where most of our graduates were going.
Your outfit nickname, what was its nickname?
My what?
Your Corps outfit.
Oh, it was B-Signal Corps.
Did it have a nickname?
Yeah, they sure did.
They all had nicknames.
Signal Corps was Signal Crappers.
Engineers were Crapper Builders.
Infantry were Paddle Feet.
Chemical Warfare were Stink Bombers.
And Field Artillery was Buggy Bitches.
And Calvary was jock swabbers.
Let's see.
What did you, that first year, what did you and your friends do when you didn't have anything on campus you had to do?
What did y'all do for fun?
There wasn't much place to have any fun here.
They did have a beer place across from the North Gate, but that was the only liquor you had in the county.
You might go over and drink a beer.
They had the theater was the assembly hall.
This is now where the All Faith Chapel is, so we could go to movies and go into brine.
They had
two movie houses there.
The campus theater opened that year.
And we had to boycott the Bryan Theaters for that reason.
I'm not sure why we could only go to the campus theater.
You mean the students?
The students.
The upperclassmen said we're boycotting the Bryan Theaters, so we didn't go.
We had to hitchhike into Bryan.
They did have a bus system, but we never used it.
And they had some taxes.
How many nights, on the average, did you have that you didn't feel you had to be studying?
The only night was Wednesday night.
And this is to go to church.
And then Saturday and Sunday were pretty well free.
Did you go to any church activities on Wednesday night?
No, I didn't.
But there were Wednesday night services available.
Oh, yes.
On Saturday night, where did you and your friends usually go?
Well, there wasn't much to do on Saturday night, really.
I remember we hitchhiked.
One classmate and I hitchhiked to Houston to see Gone with the Wind.
But on the weekends, we all took off and most everybody had to hitchhike.
There was only one man in the outfit that had a car.
And of course, the cars, you had to park in a certain place and leave them there all week.
You couldn't drive on campus on them.
You could get in the car and go into Brown or something like that.
During any of your years, describe your hitchhiking experiences.
Where did you catch the ride?
Give some examples of pleasant or unpleasant experiences with hitchhiking.
Well, we had a very definite rule.
You couldn't upstage.
For instance, if you hitchhiked north, you had to go out here to the north gate, and you put your suitcase down in line, and you worked your way up, and they took how many?
Or you could go into Bryan, there was a place there.
The same way in Dallas, the same way in Houston.
Where was the Dallas place to catch a ride?
It's going out Lamar Boulevard, about where the soap factory is and this sort of thing.
You couldn't hitchhike any, you couldn't go any further upstream than that.
You couldn't be an upstreamer.
And normally you allowed how long to go from Dallas to College Station?
It's hard to say.
Sometimes you spent on the road all night.
Did you ever have any unpleasant hitchhiking experiences?
No, I really didn't.
I've had it snow on us coming back from Dallas.
Usually you tried to hitchhike probably down 75, which is now 45, to Madisonville, and you hitchhiked over from Madisonville or from San Antonio and
you'd go up through Austin that way and come across.
You'd almost have to go and hitchhike across to Hearn because there just wasn't any traffic straight across to Austin.
I have not yet interviewed anyone who had a negative hitchhiking experience.
About hitchhiking?
In all my experience, I don't think anybody had any problems at all.
I've not yet found anyone who did.
No?
What about some pranks, some good bull that you remember during your student days, whether you were involved or not?
In what?
Describe some good bulls, some pranks, some jokes that students played on Sunday.
Well, I don't think we were as bad as some, but what happened was it snowed.
So this was the opportunity then for the freshmen to take the sophomores, take their clothes off and throw them in the snow.
Well, it hadn't snowed the year before, so we got to throw the juniors in the snow, too.
Now, did they retaliate?
No, they didn't.
It was just good bull, you might say.
They put up with it.
Did you all ever have any imaginative drown-outs or anything like that?
Oh, yeah, there was always drown-outs, particularly some freshman that you didn't like.
He was so adept at it, he could...
His name was Tom Robb, and we've never seen him since that.
I don't know what it was.
He was kind of a negative personality.
But, oh, we had drownouts.
How did your life change your sophomore year?
Compare sophomore Aggie life to freshman.
Well, of course, then we were hazed to freshman, and...
We were still under the juniors and seniors, but we didn't really get any study out of them particularly.
At the end of our sophomore year, the juniors picked a best drill cadet.
And the reason for this is that he became the first sergeant next year as a junior, and then he became the company commander as a senior.
So this was the steps in which he went through the ranks and this sort of thing.
The, as a sophomore, though, what, what were you, what did you do, what were your particular concerns with the freshmen?
Oh, just keep them in line, you might say.
As time went on, the war had started then, and pretty soon, and by the time I became company commander,
I mean, many of them had left already, and I just pretty well got a lot of that stuff cut out.
I mean, it's kind of childish, you might say, immaturity and this sort of thing.
And so these things kind of dropped off.
Now, you're here two years, 39-40 and 40-41?
Oh, I stayed until the fall of 42.
I was in my fourth year, but I didn't graduate.
In fact, what happened,
When the war broke out after two years, then we went to summer school.
And so after the third year starting, then we went all summer school.
And so our seniors had gone to summer camp as part of their ROTC contract to get their commission.
And so then when they finished four years,
Even though they didn't get their degree, they got their commission and went on into the service.
Up until that time, you had to have a degree before you got that.
And so far as we were concerned then, we went to summer school all that summer in 42, and then the fall semester in 43, we pretty well finished up in December.
I didn't.
I went in to get a student.
So we got on to OCS.
Well, some of us had their commission, and two of them at least said, I don't want to go to the FCS.
So they just took direct commissions in the Navy.
And so by that time, so many of them had dropped out of school.
If they didn't have a contract, they were subject to the draft.
And so many of them went ahead and joined up, particularly as pilots.
A lot of them went in the Air Force, the Wild Blue Yonder and all that stuff.
And this is where my only classmates that were lost in the war
had gone into the service, and they were killed as part of their action training.
Go back, you got here just as World War II started.
That's right.
Were you and your classmates, did you all, in the fall of 39, did you all talk much about what was happening in Europe?
Oh, of course, we were concerned, and yet it still seemed to be remote.
It wasn't until we got into the war in December that we really realized how serious everything was for us.
I presume one of the big events in the fall of 1939 was A&M football.
Yes, we were national champions.
That's 60 years ago.
That's the first time we ever won.
It's also the last time we ever won.
I went to the Sugar Bowl.
Describe that trip.
Oh, okay.

Well, my daddy was in Houston at the time doing some business, so I rode the train to Houston, and then he joined me, and we went over on the train to the Sugar Bowl game, and we went to the Sugar Bowl game together, stayed together over there, and then we came back, and we came on back home.
So, oh, we found a room there somewhere, and then ate at Antoine's, I think.
It's still there.
And that was the extent of it, and it was a nice trip.
Did you wear your uniform?
Oh, yeah, I wore the uniform.
In fact, we wore the uniform all the time.
Once you got home, you'd get out of uniform, but in general, you always hitchhiked in the uniform because it was easier to get a ride.
At the Sugar Bowl game, I presume that y'all, all kinds of Aggie traditions of standing up and yells and all of that, that was a
Oh, yes, this was current then as we stood up during all the games, but out-of-town games, it depended on the size of us, whether the rest of the crowd would let us stand up or not.
You don't recall what the ticket cost, do you?
What, what?
The Sugar Bowl ticket.
I wonder what it cost.
I don't know, but I've got a program from that game.
A couple of dollars, I imagine.
The...
Did you get acquainted with any of the heroes of that football team?
Okay.
At the second semester of my freshman year, I took Chemistry 102 under Tom Harrington.
I was in his class, and the guy that sat right next in front of me was Ernie Pannell.
Pannell.
He was a tackle.
And he was taking freshman chemistry.
Here he was, a junior.
So I kind of got acquainted with him.
But that's really, I didn't have much acquainted with him.
Because they all lived in Domitory 12.
This is the athletic dorm.
So that's where the athletes lived.
But officially, they were in the Corps?
Well, they were all in the Corps.
And they wore their uniforms to class.
Oh, yeah.
Describe Professor Harrington and his course and
Describe him as a teacher and a faculty member.
Well, of course he was a good instructor.
At that time he was a prof, and later on that he moved on up.
But he didn't, you've got three times a week in a small classroom, once a week in the large lecture room.
Once in a while he would lecture there, but usually it was a more senior professor would lecture in chemistry.
I can't think of his name now, but anyway.
Did you all have a nickname for Dr. Harrington?
I can't remember that, no.
Most profs did have one, though.
My own electrical engineering profs all had nicknames.
Every prof on the campus almost had one.
Share some of those.
Well, there was Dutch Dillingham, because he was a Dutchman.
There was Rabbi Markle.
He looked Jewish, so they called him Rabbi.
Pappy Foraker.
Firecracker Road, Bear Tracks Bolton, and a four-acre son became the dean of the business administration.
And he came back for this reunion when I had all the signal core over here to the house, and so he and his wife came over and we had a real nice visit.
He was also honored with a scholarship, and also his wife.
Her father was a civil engineering prop, and he was known as Shaky Orr because he had a trimmer.
But anyway, he came back for that, and they asked me to talk about the father, and Foiker was so nice to me afterwards.
And then he came over here.
Well, of course, all these guys that had the daddy in class,
And so they told lots of stories about his father and this sort of thing.
And he was on the golf team while he was here.
And he said when he was a kid, he would come over and sit on the steps of Bolton Hall until his daddy finished class for the day.
And then he would go home with him because he lived off campus.
And he just died in the past year of pneumonia.
Describe where most of your classes were held.
What buildings?
Of course, Bolton Hall was electrical engineering.
Next door to it is mechanical engineering, Fermier Hall.
And then the academic building is where we had most of all of our other courses.
Civil engineering was across from Enagle Hall.
That's where civil engineering was.
And then the mechanical engineering had shop building next door.
And so we had our steam lab, our lab courses over there, a machine shop, and this sort of thing.
So most all of them were right there in those buildings right there.
The chemistry was down in the... Chemistry was in its building, of course.
And physics.
And physics was over in its building.
What about math?
And math was in the academic building.
All the courses were in the academic building for math.
and for English and for history and for government.
What about some English teachers?
English?
Well, there's old Brooks Cofer's daddy, which we called Dusty Cofer, John Paul Abbott.
What was his nickname?
John Paul Abbott, he just went by that, yeah.
But then there was, for history, was a guy named Count Segarra.
Segarff was a Hungarian, I believe, but anyway, he was called Count Segarff.
And I remember one day, this guy was quoting from the history book, and he quoted from it, and he says, where did you get that?
I says, from the history book.
He says, well, throw it out the window.
So the guy threw it out the window.
Yeah, of course, the egg.
They were all good profs, I felt like.
They really were.
The math, I had Klippel way back there and people like that.
Describe the routine of typical Aggie classes.
How did the students behave?
How did the faculty member conduct the class and so forth?
I can never remember any disturbance of any kind in any of those classes, yeah.
What if a student went to sleep?
Did a student dare go to sleep in class?
I guess they did.
I don't remember.
I don't think I did.
Was the faculty available out of class if you wanted to go talk to them?
I can't remember.
I didn't use them that much.
Really, it's surprising.
Most of the faculty and staff lived on campus, didn't they?
Well, I'd say a smaller and smaller percentage, because in 1939, the board said we've got to get all these houses off campus, and by 1942, they would all be moved off.
So this is the way it turned out.
Because when I interviewed, when I chatted with Henry Gilchrist, he told me that in 1937, when they arrived,
the A&M Consolidated School District was about to finish their new building on the south side of Jersey Street and move it off campus.
In 1939, they were still in Pfeiffer Hall and the Music Hall.
And within the next year, they had moved over to what is now George Bush Drive.
As you look back on your student academic days,
What were the emphasis, what was the emphasis for you as an electrical engineer?
What were they preparing you for?
Oh, it was mostly power.
You had a course in communication which would be used both for telethy and power systems, but by and large we took the circuits,
and in the spring we'd take the DC machinery, and then AC circuits in your junior year, and you'd get into transmission, and you took a course in economics.
The senior year was both machinery courses, and each one had an extensive lab.
And so we really weren't getting much into electronics at all.
We did have a
I liked Donnie's course, but it was all vacuum tubes, and you could see how limited it was there.
It's unbelievable what's happened.
In the early 1960s, Dr. Bolton and I went to Houston back for a meeting, and when he got out of the car, he says, I have seen so much happen in the past 50 years.
